item.title: The U.S. Finally Has a Strategy to Compete With China. Will It Work?
item.description: The strategy, which took seven years to come together, is a three-legged stool consisting of tariffs, security restrictions and tech subsidies.

item.title: Palestinians Struggle for Food and Water After Fleeing Rafah
item.description: Many of the 800,000 who left the city huddle in tents on a crowded beach, with little in the way of amenities or humanitarian aid. “It’s a constant battle for survival,” a refugee says.

item.title: Li Auto's First-Quarter Net Profit Fell Despite Higher Revenue
item.description: The Chinese electric-vehicle maker’s first-quarter net profit dropped 36% despite higher revenue, though the company maintained a gross margin above 20%.

item.title: Gold Futures Near Record High as Interest-Rate Cut Hopes Grow
item.description: Gold futures were just shy of their recent record as softer U.S. data last week raised expectations of Fed interest rate cuts.

item.title: Oil Prices Rise But Stay Stuck in Narrow Range
item.description: Oil futures edged higher with the market awaiting OPEC’s next move, with three possible scenarios for the June 1 meeting—extend, unwind or completely remove the voluntary cuts of 2.2 million barrels a day.

item.title: Keywords Shares Have Best Ever Day as EQT Talks Confirmed
item.description: Keywords Studios stock soared after the videogame services company said it was in talks with EQT over a potential $2.6 billion takeover, which would make it the latest in a series of companies to leave the London Exchange if the deal goes ahead.

item.title: Chinese Shares End Higher; Commodity Stocks Lead Gains
item.description: China’s benchmark Shanghai Composite ended 0.5% higher, as sentiment remained positive following Beijing’s stimulus measures targeting the property sector.

item.title: USD/SGD's Downward Momentum Starting to Build, Charts Show
item.description: USD/SGD’s downward momentum is starting to build after it fell to a low of 1.3421 last week, said UOB Global Economics & Markets Research.

item.title: AstraZeneca Plans $1.5 Billion Manufacturing Facility In Singapore
item.description: The Anglo-Swedish pharmaceutical giant plans to build a $1.5 billion manufacturing facility in Singapore to boost its global supply of cancer-killing treatments.

item.title: Iranian President, Foreign Minister Killed in Helicopter Crash
item.description: Ebrahim Raisi’s death deprives Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei of a longtime ally as Tehran angles for regional dominance.

item.title: Europe Sees Signs of Russian Sabotage but Hesitates to Blame Kremlin
item.description: Governments have warned of acute threats but often stopped short of accusing Moscow over a lack of evidence and concern about spreading panic at home.

item.title: Many Armies Struggle for Recruits. In Sweden They Turn Them Away.
item.description: American and European militaries are straining to reinforce their ranks to deter Russia. Sweden’s answer is to conscript only the brightest and best.

item.title: Ryanair Announces Buyback as Profits Jump
item.description: The low-cost carrier will buy back $761 million worth of shares after its core earnings for the fiscal year rose 34%, and said it expected passenger numbers to increase depending on how well Boeing handles its delivery delays.

item.title: Behind New Caledonia's Riots, a Fight Over Vast Reserves of Nickel
item.description: France has a plan to lift restrictions on exports of the archipelago’s nickel to supply clean-energy manufacturing, drawing condemnation from indigenous leaders.

item.title: New Taiwan President Swings at China---but Pulls Punches---in First Speech
item.description: Lai Ching-te gave a carefully calibrated inauguration speech that reflected his delicate status at the fulcrum of tensions between the U.S. and China.

item.title: China Hints at Possible Retaliation Against EU Probes
item.description: China has hinted at potential retaliation in response to the European Union’s investigations into Chinese companies, and launched a probe into chemical imports.

item.title: Red Lobster Files for Bankruptcy
item.description: Red Lobster, the largest seafood restaurant chain in the U.S., has filed for bankruptcy protection in an effort to reduce debt and will sell its assets.

item.title: Iranian President Ebrahim Raisi, a Hard-Liner With Supreme Leader's Backing, Dies at 63
item.description: Raisi was killed in a helicopter crash in northwestern Iran hours after meeting Azerbaijan’s leader.

item.title: Gold's Global Rally Is Sparking a New Investor Class
item.description: Gold is hitting record highs— bucking long held trends for the commodity. WSJ breaks down the factors behind its rally and why that’s bringing in a new class of investors.

item.title: Behind Zuckerberg's contrarian strategy to give away Meta's artificial-intelligence technology is a bet that making Silicon Valley's hottest new offering free will drive down competitors' prices and spread Meta's version more broadly.
